Number of Set Bits (Hamming Weight)

Given a positive integer n, write a function that returns the number of 
set bits in its binary representation (also known as the Hamming weight).

Example 1:
Input: n = 11
Output: 3
Explanation:
The input binary string 1011 has a total of three set bits.

Example 2:
Input: n = 128
Output: 1
Explanation:
The input binary string 10000000 has a total of one set bit.

Example 3:
Input: n = 2147483645
Output: 30
Explanation:
The input binary string 1111111111111111111111111111101 has a total of thirty set bits.

Constraints:
1 <= n <= 2^31 - 1

--------------------------------------------------

Approach 1

class Solution 
{
public:
    int hammingWeight(int n)
    {   
        int count=0;
        for(int i=31;i>=0;i--)
        {
            if((n>>i&1)==1)
                count++;
        }
        return count;
    }
};

Time Complexity: O(1)

--------------------------------------------------

Approach 2

class Solution {
public:
    int hammingWeight(int n)
    {   
        int count=0;
        while(n>0)
        {
            n=n&(n-1);       // at each time unset rightmost bit.
            count++;
        }
        return count;
    }
};

Time Complexity: O(k)  
k = number of set bits

--------------------------------------------------

Approach 3

class Solution {
public:
    int hammingWeight(int n)
    {   
        int count=0;
        while(n!=0)
        {
            count+=n%2;
            n=n/2;
        }
        return count;
    }
};

Time Complexity: O(log n)

--------------------------------------------------

Approach 4

class Solution 
{
public:
    int hammingWeight(int n)
    {
        return __builtin_popcount(n);
    }
};

Time Complexity: O(1)
